description.value: East Greek terracotta figure vase (plastic vase). Reconstructed from two joined fragments of aryballos in the form of a swan. Swan is represented swimming with head arched back. Tail damaged and spout lost. Mould-made with 'black glaze' slip, applied white (faded) and red paint and incised detail. Head is black with white spots, eyes incised and surrounded with white spots. Wings are black with red and white dots on front part, then a red line, then long line of incisions. The tail is black and the legs red. Orange-brown fine Milesian (?) clay fabric with common very fine mica inclusions.

description.value: egyptian terracotta askos or flask in form of pig or boar. The vessel has a cylindrical neck with a flaring mouth rising from the back of the pig; a spout, broken at its tip, is placed at the animal’s nose. The body was thrown on the wheel and then manipulated into shape, with several applied elements: the neck of the flask, the feet, the ridged mane, the ears. The tail may have been applied or modelled from the thrown pot (its tip is broken), and the eyes were formed by pressing a hollow rod into the soft clay. Red-brown Nile silt with abundant gold mica, quartz and white inclusions. Covered, except the underbelly, with a creamy white slip.

description.value: Axe-head: bound to its original haft. The blade is splayed and its cutting edge narrow. The sides are gently bevelled. The edge shows signs of wear. description.value: Model axe-blade: of the rounded form but without any perforation,  as this was probably considered unnecessary in a model. The blade has been cut from thin sheet copper, with the un-sharpened edge roughly shaped in a convex curve, whilst the butt is straight. The surfaces are covered with a thin layer of corrosion.

description.value: Rectangular, almost square, axe-head: with slightly convex sides, roughly made. The butt is uneven and one of the sides is longer than the other. The blade is thickly corroded, especially at the cutting edge, which appears originally to have been very slightly convex with rounded corners. The metal is considerably pitted,   particularly around the peripheries of the tool.

description.value: Shallow asymmetrical arsenical copper axe-head:  of quite rough work. It is a little warped and has an uneven butt. The upper end is squared, the lower rounded. There are five binding-holes. The blade is quite thickly corroded and the cutting edge is damaged. The line of the haft is preserved.
